# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-iam
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-iam/access-control] In physical security and information security, **access control** (**AC**) is the action of deciding whether a subject should be granted or denied access to an object (for example, a place or a resource).
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The act of *accessing* may mean consuming, entering, or using.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] It is often used interchangeably with authorization, although the authorization may be granted well in advance of the access control decision.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Access control on digital platforms is also termed admission control.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The protection of external databases is essential to preserve digital security.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Access control is considered to be a significant aspect of privacy that should be further studied.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] **Access control policy** (also **access policy**) is part of an organization’s security policy.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] In order to verify the access control policy, organizations use an access control model.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] General security policies require designing or selecting appropriate security controls to satisfy an organization's risk appetite - access policies similarly require the organization to design or select access controls.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Broken access control is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] On the basis of the "principle of least privilege", consumers should only be authorized to access whatever they need to do their jobs, and nothing more.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Geographical access control may be enforced by personnel (e.g. border guard, bouncer, ticket checker), or with a device such as a turnstile.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] There may be fences to avoid circumventing this access control.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] An alternative of access control in the strict sense (physically controlling access itself) is a system of checking authorized presence, see e.g.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] A variant is exit control, e.g. of a shop (checkout) or a country.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The term access control refers to the practice of restricting entrance to a property, a building, or a room to authorized persons.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Physical access control can be achieved by a human (a guard, bouncer, or receptionist), through mechanical means such as locks and keys, or through technological means such as access control systems like the mantrap.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Within these environments, physical key management may also be employed as a means of further managing and monitoring access to mechanically keyed areas or access to certain small assets.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Physical access control is a matter of who, where, and when.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] An access control system determines who is allowed to enter or exit, where they are allowed to exit or enter, and when they are allowed to enter or exit.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Historically, this was partially accomplished through keys and locks.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] When a door is locked, only someone with a key can enter through the door, depending on how the lock is configured.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not allow restriction of the key holder to specific times or dates.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not provide records of the key used on any specific door, and the keys can be easily copied or transferred to an unauthorized person.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] When a mechanical key is lost or the key holder is no longer authorized to use the protected area, the locks must be re-keyed.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Electronic access control (EAC) uses computers to solve the limitations of mechanical locks and keys.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] It is particularly difficult to guarantee identification (a critical component of authentication) with mechanical locks and keys.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] A wide range of credentials can be used to replace mechanical keys, allowing for complete authentication, authorization, and accounting.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The electronic access control system grants access based on the credential presented.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] When access is granted, the resource is unlocked for a predetermined time and the transaction is recorded.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] When access is refused, the resource remains locked and the attempted access is recorded.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The system will also monitor the resource and alarm if the resource is forcefully unlocked or held open too long after being unlocked.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] When a credential is presented to a reader, the reader sends the credential's information, usually a number, to a control panel, a highly reliable processor.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The control panel compares the credential's number to an access control list, grants or denies the presented request, and sends a transaction log to a database.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] When access is denied based on the access control list, the door remains locked.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] If there is a match between the credential and the access control list, the control panel operates a relay that in turn unlocks the resource.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The control panel also ignores an opening signal to prevent an alarm.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Often the reader provides feedback, such as a flashing red LED for an access denied and a flashing green LED for an access granted.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The above description illustrates a single factor transaction.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Credentials can be passed around, thus subverting the access control list.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] For example, Alice has access rights to the server room, but Bob does not.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Alice either gives Bob her credential, or Bob takes it; he now has access to the server room.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] To prevent this, two-factor authentication can be used.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] In a two factor transaction, the presented credential and a second factor are needed for access to be granted; another factor can be a PIN code, a second credential, operator intervention, or a biometric input.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Passwords are a common means of verifying a user's identity before access is given to information systems.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] In addition, a fourth factor of authentication is now recognized: someone you know, whereby another person who knows you can provide a human element of authentication in situations where systems have been set up to allow for such scenarios.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] For example, a user may have their password, but have forgotten their smart card.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] In such a scenario, if the user is known to designated cohorts, the cohorts may provide their smart card and password, in combination with the extant factor of the user in question, and thus provide two factors for the user with the missing credential, giving three factors overall to allow access.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] A credential is a physical/tangible object, a piece of knowledge, or a facet of a person's physical being that enables an individual access to a given physical facility or computer-based information system.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Typically, credentials can be something a person knows (such as a number or PIN code), something they have (such as an access badge), something they are (such as a biometric feature), something they do (measurable behavioural patterns), or some combination of these items.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] This is known as multi-factor authentication.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The typical credential is an access card or key-fob, and newer software can also turn users' smartphones into access devices.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] There are many card technologies including magnetic stripe, bar code, Wiegand, 125 kHz proximity, 26-bit card-swipe, contact smart cards, and contactless smart cards.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Also available are key-fobs, which are more compact than ID cards, and attach to a key ring.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Biometric technologies include fingerprint, facial recognition, iris recognition, retinal scan, voice, and hand geometry.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The built-in biometric technologies found on newer smartphones can also be used as credentials in conjunction with access software running on mobile devices.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] In addition to older more traditional card access technologies, newer technologies such as near-field communication (NFC), Bluetooth low energy or Ultra-wideband (UWB) can also communicate user credentials to readers for system or building access.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Access control decisions are made by comparing the credentials to an access control list.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] This look-up can be done by a host or server, by an access control panel, or by a reader.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The development of access control systems has observed a steady push of the look-up out from a central host to the edge of the system, or the reader.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The predominant topology circa 2009 is hub and spoke with a control panel as the hub, and the readers as the spokes.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The look-up and control functions are by the control panel.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The spokes communicate through a serial connection; usually RS-485.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Some manufactures are pushing the decision making to the edge by placing a controller at the door.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Some readers may have additional features such as a display and function buttons for data collection purposes (i.e. clock-in/clock-out events for attendance reports), camera/speaker/microphone for intercom, or smart card read/write support.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] All the RS-485-related advantages and disadvantages also apply.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The advantages and disadvantages of IP controllers apply to the IP readers as well.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The most common security risk of intrusion through an access control system is by simply following a legitimate user through a door, referred to as "tailgating".
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Often, a legitimate user may hold the door for the intruder as an act of common courtesy.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] This risk can be minimized through security awareness training of the user population, or more active means such as turnstiles which admit only one person at a time.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] In very high-security applications, this risk is minimized by using a sally port (sometimes called a "security vestibule" or "mantrap"), where operator intervention is required, presumably after confirming valid identification.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The second most common risk is from levering a door open by sheer brute force.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] This is relatively difficult on properly-secured doors with ruggedized strikes or high holding force magnetic locks.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Fully-implemented access control systems include forced-door monitoring alarms.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] These vary in effectiveness, often failing from high false-positive alarms, poor database configuration, or lack of active intrusion monitoring.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Most newer access control systems incorporate some type of "door prop" alarm to inform system administrators of a door left open longer than a specified length of time.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The third most common security risk arises from natural disasters.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] In order to mitigate this risk, the structure of the building, down to the quality of the network and computer equipment is crucial.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] From an organizational perspective, the leadership will need to adopt and implement an All Hazards Plan, or Incident Response Plan.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The highlights of any incident plan recommended by the National Incident Management System usually include pre-incident planning, during-incident actions, disaster recovery, and after-action review.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] An attack similar to levering is breaking through cheap partition walls, typically made of wallboard or cinder blocks.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] In shared tenant spaces, the divisional wall is a vulnerability.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] A vulnerability along the same lines is the breaking of sidelight windows located next to doors.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Spoofing of locking hardware is fairly simple and more elegant than levering.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] A strong magnet can operate the solenoid controlling bolts in electric locking hardware.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Motorized locks, more prevalent in Europe than in the US, are also susceptible to this attack using a doughnut-shaped magnet.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] It is also possible to manipulate the power to the lock either by removing or adding current, although most Access Control systems incorporate battery back-up systems, and the locks are almost always located on the secure side of the door.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Access cards themselves have proven vulnerable to sophisticated attacks.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Enterprising hackers have built portable readers that capture the card number from a user's proximity card.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The hacker simply walks by the user, reads the card, and later presents the number to a reader securing the door.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] This is possible when card numbers are sent in the clear, no encryption being used.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] To counter this, dual authentication methods, such as a card plus a PIN should always be used.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Many access control credentials use unique serial numbers which are programmed in sequential order during manufacturing.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] In a method known as a "sequential attack", if an intruder has a credential once used in the system, they can simply increment or decrement the serial number until they find a credential that is currently authorized in the system.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Specifying credentials with random unique serial numbers is recommended to counter this threat.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] In addition, increasingly long lockout timeout intervals after a credential failure will make automated repeated attacks infeasible.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Finally, most electric locking hardware still uses mechanical keys as a fail-over.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Most conventional mechanical key locks are vulnerable to bumping.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] In computer security, general access control includes authentication, authorization, and audit.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] A more narrow definition of access control would cover only access approval, whereby the system makes a decision to grant or reject an access request from an already authenticated subject, based on what the subject is authorized to access.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Authentication and access control are often combined into a single operation, so that access is approved based on successful authentication, or based on an anonymous access token.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Authentication methods and tokens include passwords, biometric analysis, physical keys, electronic keys and devices, hidden paths, social barriers, and monitoring by humans and automated systems.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] In any access-control model, the entities that can perform actions on the system are called *subjects*, and the entities representing resources to which access may need to be controlled are called *objects* (see also Access Control Matrix).
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Subjects and objects should both be considered as software entities, rather than as human users: any human users can only have an effect on the system via the software entities that they control.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] In some models, for example the object-capability model, any software entity can potentially act as both subject and object.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] As of 2014, access-control models tend to fall into one of two classes: those based on capabilities and those based on access control lists (ACLs).
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Both capability-based and ACL-based models have mechanisms to allow access rights to be granted to all members of a *group* of subjects (often the group is itself modeled as a subject).
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Access to accounts can be enforced through many types of controls.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Discretionary Access Control (DAC) In DAC, the data owner determines who can access specific resources.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] For example, a system administrator may create a hierarchy of files to be accessed based on certain permissions.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Graph-based Access Control (GBAC) Compared to other approaches like RBAC or ABAC, the main difference is that in GBAC access rights are defined using an organizational query language instead of total enumeration.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] History-Based Access Control (HBAC) Access is granted or declined based on the real-time evaluation of a history of activities of the inquiring party, e.g. behavior, time between requests, content of requests.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] For example, the access to a certain service or data source can be granted or declined on the personal behavior, e.g. the request interval exceeds one query per second.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] History-of-Presence Based Access Control (HPBAC) Access control to resources is defined in terms of presence policies that need to be satisfied by presence records stored by the requestor.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Policies are usually written in terms of frequency, spread and regularity.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Identity-Based Access Control (IBAC) Using this network administrators can more effectively manage activity and access based on individual needs.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Lattice-Based Access Control (LBAC) A lattice is used to define the levels of security that an object may have and that a subject may have access to.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The subject is only allowed to access an object if the security level of the subject is greater than or equal to that of the object.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Mandatory Access Control (MAC) In MAC, users do not have much freedom to determine who has access to their files.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] For example, security clearance of users and classification of data (as confidential, secret or top secret) are used as security labels to define the level of trust.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Organization-Based Access Control (OrBAC) OrBAC model allows the policy designer to define a security policy independently of the implementation.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Relationship-Based Access Control (ReBAC) A subject's permission to access a resource is defined by the presence of relationships between those subjects and resources.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) RBAC allows access based on the job title.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] RBAC largely eliminates discretion when providing access to objects.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] For example, a human resources specialist should not have permissions to create network accounts; this should be a role reserved for network administrators.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Rule-Based Access Control (RAC) RAC method, also referred to as Rule-Based Role-Based Access Control (RB-RBAC), is largely context based.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Example of this would be allowing students to use labs only during a certain time of day; it is the combination of students' RBAC-based information system access control with the time-based lab access rules.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Responsibility Based Access Control Information is accessed based on the responsibilities assigned to an actor or a business role.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Subscription-Based Access Control (SBAC) SBAC assigns permissions based on a user's subscription status, automating the process of granting, modifying, or revoking access as users subscribe, upgrade, downgrade, or cancel.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] SBAC is particularly relevant for SaaS business, where access to features, data, or services is tied to a user's active plan.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Unlike RBAC or ABAC, which define permissions based on roles or attributes, SBAC dynamically distributes roles and policies based on billing status, ensuring real-time access alignment.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Several regulatory frameworks impose specific access control requirements on organizations handling sensitive data.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to implement technical access controls for electronic protected health information (ePHI), including unique user identification, emergency access procedures, automatic logoff, and encryption and decryption mechanisms.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The proposed HIPAA Security Rule update (NPRM, December 2024) would strengthen these requirements by mandating multi-factor authentication for all access to ePHI.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 7 mandates that access to cardholder data be restricted on a need-to-know basis, while Requirement 8 requires unique identification for each person with computer access.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) addresses access control extensively in Special Publication 800-53 through the AC (Access Control) control family, which includes policies for account management, separation of duties, least privilege, and session controls.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] A technique used to define or restrict the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data onto, a storage device.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The definition or restriction of the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data into, a storage device.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] The process of limiting access to the resources of an AIS (Automated Information System) to authorized users, programs, processes, or other systems.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] That function performed by the resource controller that allocates system resources to satisfy user requests.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] This definition depends on several other technical terms from Federal Standard 1037C.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] Special public member methods – **accessors** (aka **getters**) and **mutator methods** (often called **setters**) are used to control changes to class variables in order to prevent unauthorized access and data corruption.
[src:aws-iam/access-control] In public policy, access control to restrict access to systems ("authorization") or to track or monitor behavior within systems ("accountability") is an implementation feature of using trusted systems for security or social control.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC is a method of implementing access control policies that is highly adaptable and can be customized using a wide range of attributes, making it suitable for use in distributed or rapidly changing environments.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] The only limitations on the policies that can be implemented with ABAC are the capabilities of the computational language and the availability of relevant attributes.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC policy rules are generated as Boolean functions of the subject's attributes, the object's attributes, and the environment attributes.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Unlike role-based access control (RBAC), which defines roles that carry a specific set of privileges associated with them and to which subjects are assigned, ABAC can express complex rule sets that can evaluate many different attributes.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Through defining consistent subject and object attributes into security policies, ABAC eliminates the need for explicit authorizations to individuals’ subjects needed in a non-ABAC access method, reducing the complexity of managing access lists and groups.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Attribute values can be set-valued or atomic-valued.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Set-valued attributes contain more than one atomic value.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Atomic-valued attributes contain only one atomic value.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Examples are *clearance* and *sensitivity*.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Attributes can be compared to static values or to one another, thus enabling relation-based access control.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control is sometimes referred to as **policy-based access control** (**PBAC**) or **claims-based access control** (**CBAC**), which is a Microsoft-specific term.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] The key standards that implement ABAC are XACML and ALFA (XACML).
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] The PDP or Policy Decision Point is the brain of the architecture.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] This is the piece which evaluates incoming requests against policies it has been configured with.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] The PIP or Policy Information Point bridges the PDP to external sources of attributes e.g.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Attributes can be about anything and anyone.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Policies are statements that bring together attributes to express what can happen and is not allowed.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Policies in ABAC can be granting or denying policies.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Policies can also be local or global and can be written in a way that they override other policies.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] With ABAC you can have an unlimited number of policies that cater to many different scenarios and technologies.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Historically, access control models have included mandatory access control (MAC), discretionary access control (DAC), and more recently role-based access control (RBAC).
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] These access control models are user-centric and do not take into account additional parameters such as resource information, the relationship between the user (the requesting entity) and the resource, and dynamic information, e.g. time of the day or user IP.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC tries to address this by defining access control based on attributes which describe the requesting entity (the user), the targeted object or resource, the desired action (view, edit, delete), and environmental or contextual information.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] This is why access control is said to be attribute-based.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] XACML, the eXtensible Access Control Markup Language, defines an architecture (shared with ALFA and NGAC), a policy language, and a request/response scheme.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] It does not handle attribute management (user attribute assignment, object attribute assignment, environment attribute assignment) which is left to traditional IAM tools, databases, and directories.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Companies, including every branch in the United States military, have started using ABAC.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] At a basic level, ABAC protects data with 'IF/THEN/AND' rules rather than assign data to users.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] The US Department of Commerce has made this a mandatory practice and the adoption is spreading throughout several governmental and military agencies.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] The concept of ABAC can be applied at any level of the technology stack and an enterprise infrastructure.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] For example, ABAC can be used at the firewall, server, application, database, and data layer.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] The use of attributes bring additional context to evaluate the legitimacy of any request for access and inform the decision to grant or deny access.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] An important consideration when evaluating ABAC solutions is to understand its potential overhead on performance and its impact on the user experience.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] It is expected that the more granular the controls, the higher the overhead.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC can be used to apply attribute-based, fine-grained authorization to the API methods or functions.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] For instance, a banking API may expose an `approveTransaction(transId)` method.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] The API receives the call and authenticates the user.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] The PDP retrieves the ABAC policy and necessary attributes.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] If the decision is Permit, the underlying API business logic is called.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Otherwise the API returns an error or access denied.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] One of the key benefits to ABAC is that the authorization policies and attributes can be defined in a technology neutral way.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] This means policies defined for APIs or databases can be reused in the application space.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] The same process and flow as the one described in the API section applies here too.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Security for databases has long been specific to the database vendors: Oracle VPD, IBM FGAC, and Microsoft RLS are all means to achieve fine-grained ABAC-like security.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Data security typically goes one step further than database security and applies control directly to the data element.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] This is often referred to as data-centric security.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] On traditional relational databases, ABAC policies can control access to data at the table, column, field, cell and sub-cell using logical controls with filtering conditions and masking based on attributes.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Attributes can be data, user, session or tools based to deliver the greatest level of flexibility in dynamically granting/denying access to a specific data element.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] On big data, and distributed file systems such as Hadoop, ABAC applied at the data layer control access to folder, sub-folder, file, sub-file and other granular.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control can also be applied to Big Data systems like Hadoop.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] Policies similar to those used previously can be applied when retrieving data from data lakes.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] As of Windows Server 2012, Microsoft has implemented an ABAC approach to controlling access to files and folders.
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] This is achieved through dynamic access control (DAC) and Security Descriptor Definition Language (SDDL).
[src:aws-iam/attribute-based-access-control] SDDL can be seen as an ABAC language as it uses metadata of the user (claims) and of the file/ folder to control access.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Authentication is relevant to multiple fields.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] In art, antiques, and anthropology, a common problem is verifying that a given artifact was produced by a certain person, or in a certain place (i.e. to assert that it is not counterfeit), or in a given period of history (e.g. by determining the age via carbon dating).
[src:aws-iam/authentication] In computer science, verifying a user's identity is often required to allow access to confidential data or systems.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] It might involve validating personal identity documents.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The *first* type of authentication is accepting proof of identity given by a credible person who has first-hand evidence that the identity is genuine.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] When authentication is required for art or physical objects, this proof could be a friend, family member, or colleague attesting to the item's provenance, perhaps by having witnessed the item in its creator's possession.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] With autographed sports memorabilia, this could involve someone attesting that they witnessed the object being signed.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] A vendor selling branded items implies authenticity, while they may not have evidence that every step in the supply chain was authenticated.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The *second* type of authentication is comparing the attributes of the object itself to what is known about objects of that origin.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] For example, an art expert might look for similarities in the style of painting, check the location and form of a signature, or compare the object to an old photograph.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] An archaeologist, on the other hand, might use carbon dating to verify the age of an artifact, do a chemical and spectroscopic analysis of the materials used, or compare the style of construction or decoration to other artifacts of similar origin.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The physics of sound and light, and comparison with a known physical environment, can be used to examine the authenticity of audio recordings, photographs, or videos.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Documents can be verified as being created on ink or paper readily available at the time of the item's implied creation.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Attribute comparison may be vulnerable to forgery.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] In general, it relies on the facts that creating a forgery indistinguishable from a genuine artifact requires expert knowledge, that mistakes are easily made, and that the amount of effort required to do so is considerably greater than the amount of profit that can be gained from the forgery.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] In art and antiques, certificates are of great importance for authenticating an object of interest and value.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Certificates can, however, also be forged, and the authentication of these poses a problem.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] For instance, the son of Han van Meegeren, the well-known art-forger, forged the work of his father and provided a certificate for its provenance as well.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Criminal and civil penalties for fraud, forgery, and counterfeiting can reduce the incentive for falsification, depending on the risk of getting caught.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Currency and other financial instruments commonly use this second type of authentication method.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Bills, coins, and cheques incorporate hard-to-duplicate physical features, such as fine printing or engraving, distinctive feel, watermarks, and holographic imagery, which are easy for trained receivers to verify.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The *third* type of authentication relies on documentation or other external affirmations.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] In criminal courts, the rules of evidence often require establishing the chain of custody of evidence presented.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] This can be accomplished through a written evidence log, or by testimony from the police detectives and forensics staff that handled it.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Some antiques are accompanied by certificates attesting to their authenticity.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Signed sports memorabilia is usually accompanied by a certificate of authenticity.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] These external records have their own problems of forgery and perjury and are also vulnerable to being separated from the artifact and lost.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Consumer goods such as pharmaceuticals, perfume, and clothing can use all forms of authentication to prevent counterfeit goods from taking advantage of a popular brand's reputation.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] As mentioned above, having an item for sale in a reputable store implicitly attests to it being genuine, the first type of authentication.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The second type of authentication might involve comparing the quality and craftsmanship of an item, such as an expensive handbag, to genuine articles.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The third type of authentication could be the presence of a trademark on the item, which is a legally protected marking, or any other identifying feature which aids consumers in the identification of genuine brand-name goods.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] With software, companies have taken great steps to protect from counterfeiters, including adding holograms, security rings, security threads and color shifting ink.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Counterfeit products are often offered to consumers as being authentic.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Counterfeit consumer goods, such as electronics, music, apparel, and counterfeit medications, have been sold as being legitimate.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Efforts to control the supply chain and educate consumers help ensure that authentic products are sold and used.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Even security printing on packages, labels, and nameplates, however, is subject to counterfeiting.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Products or their packaging can include a variable QR Code.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] A QR Code alone is easy to verify but offers a weak level of authentication as it offers no protection against counterfeits unless scan data is analyzed at the system level to detect anomalies.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] To increase the security level, the QR Code can be combined with a digital watermark or copy detection pattern that are robust to copy attempts and can be authenticated with a smartphone.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] A secure key storage device can be used for authentication in consumer electronics, network authentication, license management, supply chain management, etc.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Generally, the device to be authenticated needs some sort of wireless or wired digital connection to either a host system or a network.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Nonetheless, the component being authenticated need not be electronic in nature as an authentication chip can be mechanically attached and read through a connector to the host e.g. an authenticated ink tank for use with a printer.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] For products and services that these secure coprocessors can be applied to, they can offer a solution that can be much more difficult to counterfeit than most other options while at the same time being more easily verified.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Packaging and labeling can be engineered to help reduce the risks of counterfeit consumer goods or the theft and resale of products.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Some package constructions are more difficult to copy and some have pilfer indicating seals.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Counterfeit goods, unauthorized sales (diversion), material substitution and tampering can all be reduced with these anti-counterfeiting technologies.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Packages may include authentication seals and use security printing to help indicate that the package and contents are not counterfeit; these too are subject to counterfeiting.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Packages also can include anti-theft devices, such as dye-packs, RFID tags, or electronic article surveillance tags that can be activated or detected by devices at exit points and require specialized tools to deactivate.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] In literacy, authentication is a readers’ process of questioning the veracity of an aspect of literature and then verifying those questions via research.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The fundamental question for authentication of literature is – Does one believe it?
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Related to that, an authentication project is therefore a reading and writing activity in which students document the relevant research process.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The documentation materials for literature go beyond narrative texts and likely include informational texts, primary sources, and multimedia.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The process typically involves both internet and hands-on library research.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] When authenticating historical fiction in particular, readers consider the extent that the major historical events, as well as the culture portrayed (e.g., the language, clothing, food, gender roles), are believable for the period.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Literary forgery can involve imitating the style of a famous author.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] If an original manuscript, typewritten text, or recording is available, then the medium itself (or its packaging – anything from a box to e-mail headers) can help prove or disprove the authenticity of the document.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] However, text, audio, and video can be copied into new media, possibly leaving only the informational content itself to use in authentication.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Various systems have been invented to allow authors to provide a means for readers to reliably authenticate that a given message originated from or was relayed by them.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The opposite problem is the detection of plagiarism, where information from a different author is passed off as a person's own work.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] A common technique for proving plagiarism is the discovery of another copy of the same or very similar text, which has different attribution.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] In some cases, excessively high quality or a style mismatch may raise suspicion of plagiarism.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The process of authentication is distinct from that of authorization.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Whereas authentication is the process of verifying that "you are who you say you are", authorization is the process of verifying that "you are permitted to do what you are trying to do".
[src:aws-iam/authentication] While authorization often happens immediately after authentication (e.g., when logging into a computer system), this does not mean authorization presupposes authentication: an anonymous agent could be authorized to a limited action set.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Similarly, the establishment of the authorization can occur long before the authorization decision occurs.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] A user can be given access to secure systems based on user credentials that imply authenticity.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] A network administrator can give a user a password, or provide the user with a key card or other access devices to allow system access.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] In this case, authenticity is implied but not guaranteed.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Most secure internet communication relies on centralized authority-based trust relationships, such as those used in HTTPS, where public certificate authorities (CAs) vouch for the authenticity of websites.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] This same centralized trust model underpins protocols like OIDC (OpenID Connect) where identity providers (e.g., Google) authenticate users on behalf of relying applications.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] In contrast, decentralized peer-based trust, also known as a web of trust, is commonly used for personal services such as secure email or file sharing.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] In systems like PGP, trust is established when individuals personally verify and sign each other’s cryptographic keys, without relying on a central authority.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] These systems use cryptographic protocols that, in theory, are not vulnerable to spoofing as long as the originator’s private key remains uncompromised.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Importantly, even if the key owner is unaware of a compromise, the cryptographic failure still invalidates trust.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] However, while these methods are currently considered secure, they are not provably unbreakable—future mathematical or computational advances (such as quantum computing or new algorithmic attacks) could expose vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] If that happens, it could retroactively undermine trust in past communications or agreements.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] For example, a digitally signed contract might be challenged if the signature algorithm is later found to be insecure..
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The ways in which someone may be authenticated fall into three categories, based on what is known as the factors of authentication: something the user knows, something the user has, and something the user is.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Each authentication factor covers a range of elements used to authenticate or verify a person's identity before being granted access, approving a transaction request, signing a document or other work product, granting authority to others, and establishing a chain of authority.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Security research has determined that for a positive authentication, elements from at least two, and preferably all three, factors should be verified.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Ownership: Something the user has (e.g., wrist band, ID card, security token, implanted device, cell phone with a built-in hardware token, software token, or cell phone holding a software token).
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Inherence: Something the user is or does (e.g., fingerprint, retinal pattern, DNA sequence (there are assorted definitions of what is sufficient), signature, face, voice, unique bio-electric signals, or other biometric identifiers).
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Historically, fingerprints have been used as the most authoritative method of authentication, but court cases in the US and elsewhere have raised fundamental doubts about fingerprint reliability.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Outside of the legal system as well, fingerprints are easily spoofable, with British Telecom's top computer security official noting that "few" fingerprint readers have not already been tricked by one spoof or another.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Hybrid or two-tiered authentication methods offer a compelling solution, such as private keys encrypted by fingerprint inside of a USB device.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] As the weakest level of authentication, only a single component from one of the three categories of factors is used to authenticate an individual's identity.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The use of only one factor does not offer much protection from misuse or malicious intrusion.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] This type of authentication is not recommended for financial or personally relevant transactions that warrant a higher level of security.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Multi-factor authentication involves two or more authentication factors (something you know, something you have, or something you are).
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Two-factor authentication is a special case of multi-factor authentication involving exactly two factors.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] For example, using a bank card (something the user has) along with a PIN (something the user knows) provides two-factor authentication.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Business networks may require users to provide a password (knowledge factor) and a pseudorandom number from a security token (ownership factor).
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Access to a very-high-security system might require a mantrap screening of height, weight, facial, and fingerprint checks (several inherence factor elements) plus a PIN and a day code (knowledge factor elements), but this is still a two-factor authentication.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The United States government's National Information Assurance Glossary defines strong authentication as a layered authentication approach relying on two or more authenticators to establish the identity of an originator or receiver of information.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The European Central Bank (ECB) has defined strong authentication as "a procedure based on two or more of the three authentication factors".
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The factors that are used must be mutually independent and at least one factor must be "non-reusable and non-replicable", except in the case of an inherence factor and must also be incapable of being stolen off the Internet.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] In the European, as well as in the US-American understanding, strong authentication is very similar to multi-factor authentication or 2FA, but exceeding those with more rigorous requirements.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The FIDO Alliance has been striving to establish technical specifications for strong authentication.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Conventional computer systems authenticate users only at the initial log-in session, which can be the cause of a critical security flaw.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] To resolve this problem, systems need continuous user authentication methods that continuously monitor and authenticate users based on some biometric trait(s).
[src:aws-iam/authentication] A study used behavioural biometrics based on writing styles as a continuous authentication method.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Recent research has shown the possibility of using smartphones sensors and accessories to extract some behavioral attributes such as touch dynamics, keystroke dynamics and gait recognition.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] These attributes are known as behavioral biometrics and could be used to verify or identify users implicitly and continuously on smartphones.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The authentication systems that have been built based on these behavioral biometric traits are known as active or continuous authentication systems.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The term digital authentication, also known as electronic authentication or e-authentication, refers to a group of processes where the confidence for user identities is established and presented via electronic methods to an information system.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] The digital authentication process creates technical challenges because of the need to authenticate individuals or entities remotely over a network.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Authentication – After becoming a subscriber, the user receives an authenticator e.g., a token and credentials, such as a user name.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] He or she is then permitted to perform online transactions within an authenticated session with a relying party, where they must provide proof that he or she possesses one or more authenticators.
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Life-cycle maintenance – the CSP is charged with the task of maintaining the user's credential over the course of its lifetime, while the subscriber is responsible for maintaining his or her authenticator(s).
[src:aws-iam/authentication] Extra identity factors can be required to authenticate each party's identity.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] Authorization is closely related to access control, which is what enforces the authorization policy by deciding whether access requests to resources from (authenticated) consumers shall be approved (granted) or disapproved (rejected).
[src:aws-iam/authorization] Authorization should not be confused with authentication, which is the process of verifying someone's identity.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] Hence, access control in computer systems and networks relies on access authorization specified during configuration.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] Authorization is the responsibility of an authority, such as a department manager, within the application domain, but is often delegated to a custodian such as a system administrator.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] Authorizations are expressed as access policies in some types of "policy definition application", e.g. in the form of an access control list or a capability, or a policy administration point e.g.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] Broken authorization is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] "Anonymous consumers" or "guests", are consumers that have not been required to authenticate.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] On a distributed system, it is often desirable to grant access without requiring a unique identity.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] Familiar examples of access tokens include keys, certificates and tickets: they grant access without proving identity.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] A widely used framework for authorizing applications is OAuth 2.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] It provides a standardized way for third-party applications to obtain limited access to a user's resources without exposing their credentials.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] In modern systems, a widely used model for authorization is role-based access control (RBAC) where authorization is defined by granting subjects one or more roles, and then checking that the resource being accessed has been assigned at least one of those roles.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] However, with the rise of social media, Relationship-based access control is gaining more prominence.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] Even when access is controlled through a combination of authentication and access control lists, the problems of maintaining the authorization data is not trivial, and often represents as much administrative burden as managing authentication credentials.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] It is often necessary to change or remove a user's authorization: this is done by changing or deleting the corresponding access rules on the system.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] Using atomic authorization is an alternative to per-system authorization management, where a trusted third party securely distributes authorization information.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] In public policy, authorization is a feature of trusted systems used for security or social control.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] In banking, an authorization is a hold placed on a customer's account when a purchase is made using a debit card or credit card.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] In publishing, sometimes public lectures and other freely available texts are published without the approval of the author.
[src:aws-iam/authorization] An example is the 2002 *'The Theory of Everything: The Origin and Fate of the Universe'*, which was collected from Stephen Hawking's lectures and published without his permission as per copyright law.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] The terms "identity management" (IdM) and "identity and access management" are used interchangeably in the area of identity access management.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Identity-management systems, products, applications and platforms manage identifying and ancillary data about entities that include individuals, computer-related hardware, and software applications.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] IdM covers issues such as how users gain an identity, the roles, and sometimes the permissions that identity grants, the protection of that identity, and the technologies supporting that protection (e.g., network protocols, digital certificates, passwords, etc.).
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Identity management (IdM) is the task of controlling information about users on computers.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Such information includes information that authenticates the identity of a user, and information that describes data and actions they are authorized to access and/or perform.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] It also includes the management of descriptive information about the user and how and by whom that information can be accessed and modified.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] In addition to users, managed entities typically include hardware and network resources and even applications.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] The diagram below shows the relationship between the configuration and operation phases of IAM, as well as the distinction between identity management and access management.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Access control is the enforcement of access rights defined as part of access authorization.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Digital identity is an entity's online presence, encompassing personal identifying information (PII) and ancillary information.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] See OECD and NIST guidelines on protecting PII.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] It can be interpreted as the codification of identity names and attributes of a physical instance in a way that facilitates processing.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] A general model of identity can be constructed from a small set of axioms, for example that all identities in a given namespace are unique, or that such identities bear a specific relationship to corresponding entities in the real world.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Such an axiomatic model expresses "pure identity" in the sense that the model is not constrained by a specific application context.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] In general, an entity (real or virtual) can have multiple identities and each identity can encompass multiple attributes, some of which are unique within a given name space.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] The diagram below illustrates the conceptual relationship between identities and entities, as well as between identities and their attributes.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] In most theoretical and all practical models of digital identity, a given identity object consists of a finite set of properties (attribute values).
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] These properties record information about the object, either for purposes external to the model or to operate the model, for example in classification and retrieval.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] A "pure identity" model is strictly not concerned with the external semantics of these properties.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] The most common departure from "pure identity" in practice occurs with properties intended to assure some aspect of identity, for example a digital signature or software token which the model may use internally to verify some aspect of the identity in satisfaction of an external purpose.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] To the extent that the model expresses such semantics internally, it is not a pure model.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Contrast this situation with properties that might be externally used for purposes of information security such as managing access or entitlement, but which are simply stored, maintained and retrieved, without special treatment by the model.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] The absence of external semantics within the model qualifies it as a "pure identity" model.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Identity management can thus be defined as a set of operations on a given identity model, or more generally, as a set of capabilities with reference to it.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] In practice, identity management often expands to express how model content is to be provisioned and reconciled among multiple identity models.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] The process of reconciling accounts may also be referred to as de-provisioning.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] User access enables users to assume a specific digital identity across applications, which enables access controls to be assigned and evaluated against this identity.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] The use of a single identity for a given user across multiple systems eases tasks for administrators and users.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] It simplifies access monitoring and verification, and allows the organizations to minimize excessive privileges granted to one user.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Ensuring user access security is crucial in this process, as it involves protecting the integrity and confidentiality of user credentials and preventing unauthorized access.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Implementing robust authentication mechanisms, such as multi-factor authentication (MFA), regular security audits, and strict access controls, helps safeguard user identities and sensitive data.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] User access can be tracked from initiation to termination of user access.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] When organizations deploy an identity management process or system, their motivation is normally not primarily to manage a set of identities, but rather to grant appropriate access rights to those entities via their identities.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] In other words, access management is normally the motivation for identity management and the two sets of processes are consequently closely related.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Organizations continue to add services for both internal users and by customers.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Many such services require identity management to properly provide these services.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Increasingly, identity management has been partitioned from application functions so that a single identity can serve many or even all of an organization's activities.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] For internal use identity management is evolving to control access to all digital assets, including devices, network equipment, servers, portals, content, applications and/or products.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Services often require access to extensive information about a user, including address books, preferences, entitlements and contact information.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Since much of this information is subject to privacy and/or confidentiality requirements, controlling access to it is vital.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Identity federation comprises one or more systems that share user access and allow users to log in based on authenticating against one of the systems participating in the federation.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] This trust between several systems is often known as a "circle of trust".
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] In this setup, one system acts as the identity provider (IdP) and other systems act as service providers (SPs).
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] When a user needs to access some service controlled by SP, they first authenticate against the IdP.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Upon successful authentication, the IdP sends a secure "assertion" to the SP.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] "SAML assertions, specified using a markup language intended for describing security assertions, can be used by a verifier to make a statement to a relying party about the identity of a claimant.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] In addition to creation, deletion, modification of user identity data either assisted or self-service, identity management controls ancillary entity data for use by applications, such as contact information or location.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Putting personal information onto computer networks necessarily raises privacy concerns.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Absent proper protections, the data may be used to implement a surveillance society.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Social web and online social networking services make heavy use of identity management.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Helping users decide how to manage access to their personal information has become an issue of broad concern.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Research related to the management of identity covers disciplines such as technology, social sciences, humanities and the law.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Decentralized identity management is identity management based on decentralized identifiers (DIDs).
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Within the Seventh Research Framework Programme of the European Union from 2007 to 2013, several new projects related to Identity Management started.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] The PICOS Project investigates and develops a state-of-the-art platform for providing trust, privacy and identity management in mobile communities.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] SWIFT focuses on extending identity functions and federation to the network while addressing usability and privacy concerns and leverages identity technology as a key to integrate service and transport infrastructures for the benefit of users and the providers.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Ongoing projects include Future of Identity in the Information Society (FIDIS), GUIDE, and PRIME.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] In each organization there is normally a role or department that is responsible for managing the schema of digital identities of their staff and their own objects, which are represented by object identities or object identifiers (OID).
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] The organizational policies and processes and procedures related to the oversight of identity management are sometimes referred to as *Identity Governance and Administration* (IGA).
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] How effectively and appropriately such tools are used falls within scope of broader governance, risk management, and compliance regimes.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] An **identity-management system** refers to an information system, or to a set of technologies that can be used for enterprise or cross-network identity management.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] Identity and access management systems are central to meeting regulatory requirements across multiple sectors that mandate controls over who can access sensitive information.
[src:aws-iam/identity-management] NIST Special Publication 800-53 includes comprehensive identity and access management controls in the AC (Access Control) and IA (Identification and Authentication) control families, providing the reference framework for federal agency IAM implementations.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle means giving any user accounts or processes only those privileges which are essentially vital to perform its intended functions.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, a user account for the sole purpose of creating backups does not need to install software: hence, it has rights only to run backup and backup-related applications.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] Any other privileges, such as installing new software, are blocked.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle applies also to a personal computer user who usually does work in a normal user account, and opens a privileged, password protected account only when the situation absolutely demands it.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] When applied to users, the terms *least user access* or *least-privileged user account* (LUA) are also used, referring to the concept that all user accounts should run with as few privileges as possible, and also launch applications with as few privileges as possible.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle (of least privilege) is widely recognized as an important design consideration towards enhancing and giving a much needed 'Boost' to the protection of data and functionality from faults (fault tolerance) and malicious behavior.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, there exist multiple competing definitions of true (least privilege).
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] As program complexity increases rapidly, so do the number of potential issues, rendering a predictive approach impractical.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] Examples include the values of variables it may process, addresses it will need, or the precise time such things will be required.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] Object capability systems allow, for instance, deferring granting a single-use privilege until the time when it will be used.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] Currently, the closest practical approach is to eliminate privileges that can be manually evaluated as unnecessary.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] The resulting set of privileges typically exceeds the true minimum required privileges for the process.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] Another limitation is the granularity of control that the operating environment has over privileges for an individual process.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, it is rarely possible to control a process's access to memory, processing time, I/O device addresses or modes with the precision needed to facilitate only the precise set of privileges a process will require.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] Denning, in his paper "Fault Tolerant Operating Systems", set it in a broader perspective among "The four fundamental principles of fault tolerance".
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] "Dynamic assignments of privileges" was earlier discussed by Roger Needham in 1972.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] Historically, the oldest instance of (least privilege) is probably the source code of *login.c*, which begins execution with super-user permissions and—the instant they are no longer necessary—dismisses them via *setuid()* with a non-zero argument as demonstrated in the Version 6 Unix source code.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] The kernel always runs with maximum privileges since it is the operating system core and has hardware access.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] One of the principal responsibilities of an operating system, particularly a multi-user operating system, is management of the hardware's availability and requests to access it from running processes.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] When the kernel crashes, the mechanisms by which it maintains state also fail.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] Therefore, even if there is a way for the CPU to recover without a hard reset, security continues to be enforced, but the operating system cannot properly respond to the failure because it was not possible to detect the failure.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] This is because kernel execution either halted or the program counter resumed execution from somewhere in an endless, and—usually—non-functional loop.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] This would be akin to either experiencing amnesia (kernel execution failure) or being trapped in a closed maze that always returns to the starting point (closed loops).
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] If execution picks up after the crash by loading and running trojan code, the author of the trojan code can usurp control of all processes.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] The principle of least privilege forces code to run with the lowest privilege/permission level possible.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] This means that the code that resumes the code execution-whether trojan or simply code execution picking up from an unexpected location—would not have the ability to perform malicious or undesirable processes.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] One method used to accomplish this can be implemented in the microprocessor hardware.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] For example, in the Intel x86 architecture the manufacturer designed four (ring 0 through ring 3) running "modes" with graduated degrees of access-much like security clearance systems in defence and intelligence agencies.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] As implemented in some operating systems, processes execute with a *potential privilege set* and an *active privilege set*.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] Such privilege sets are inherited from the parent as determined by the semantics of *fork()*.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] An executable file that performs a privileged function—thereby technically constituting a component of the TCB, and concomitantly termed a trusted program or trusted process—may also be marked with a set of privileges.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] This is a logical extension of the notions of set user ID and set group ID.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] The inheritance of file privileges by a process are determined by the semantics of the *exec()* family of system calls.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] The precise manner in which potential process privileges, actual process privileges, and file privileges interact can become complex.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] In practice, least privilege is practiced by forcing a process to run with only those privileges required by the task.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] Adherence to this model is quite complex as well as error-prone.
[src:aws-iam/principle-of-least-privilege] Least privilege has also been interpreted in the context of distribution of discretionary access control (DAC) permissions, for example asserting that giving user U read/write access to file F violates least privilege if U can complete their authorized tasks with only read permission.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] In information security, **role-based access control** (**RBAC**) or **role-based security** is an approach to restricting system access to authorized users.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] It is a policy-neutral computer access control mechanism defined around roles and privileges.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] The components of RBAC, such as role-permissions, user-role and role-role relationships, make it simple to perform user assignments.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] RBAC can be used to facilitate administration of security in large organizations with hundreds of users and thousands of permissions.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Although RBAC is different from mandatory access control and discretionary access control (DAC) frameworks, it can enforce these policies.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Its approach is also different from context-based access control and access-control lists.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control and relationship-based access control are models that build on the concept of RBAC.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] A 1990s study by NIST demonstrated that RBAC addresses many needs of commercial and government organizations.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] RBAC is still commonly considered a best practice in information security management, including in implementation of information security standards related to access control.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Within an organization, roles are created for various job functions.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] The permissions to perform certain operations are assigned to specific roles.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Role authorization: A subject's active role must be authorized for the subject.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] With rule 1 above, this rule ensures that users can take on only roles for which they are authorized.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Permission authorization: A subject can exercise a permission only if the permission is authorized for the subject's active role.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] With rules 1 and 2, this rule ensures that users can exercise only permissions for which they are authorized.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Additional constraints may be applied as well, and roles can be combined in a hierarchy where higher-level roles subsume permissions owned by sub-roles.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] With the concepts of role hierarchy and constraints, one can control RBAC to create or simulate lattice-based access control (LBAC).
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Thus RBAC can be considered to be a superset of LBAC.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] A constraint places a restrictive rule on the potential inheritance of permissions from opposing roles.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Thus it can be used to achieve appropriate separation of duties.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] For example, the same person should not be allowed to both create a login account and to authorize the account creation.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] A subject may have *multiple* simultaneous sessions with/in different roles.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] RBAC is a flexible access control technology whose flexibility allows it to implement or discretionary access control (DAC) or mandatory access control (MAC).
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] DAC with groups (e.g., as implemented in POSIX file systems) can emulate RBAC.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] MAC can simulate RBAC if the role graph is restricted to a tree rather than a partially ordered set.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Prior to the development of RBAC, the Bell-LaPadula (BLP) model was synonymous with MAC, and file system permissions were synonymous with DAC.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] These were considered to be the only known models for access control: if a model was not BLP, it was considered to be a DAC model, and vice versa.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Research in the late 1990s demonstrated that RBAC falls in neither category.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Unlike context-based access control (CBAC), RBAC does not look at the message context (such as a connection's source).
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] RBAC has also been criticized for leading to role explosion, a problem in large enterprise systems which require access control of finer granularity than what RBAC can provide as roles are inherently assigned to operations and data types.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] In resemblance to CBAC, an Entity-Relationship Based Access Control system is able to secure instances of data by considering their association to the executing subject.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Access control lists (ACLs) are used in traditional discretionary access-control (DAC) systems to affect low-level data-objects.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] RBAC differs from ACL in assigning permissions to operations which change the direct-relations between several entities (see: *ACLg* below).
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] For example, an ACL could be used for granting or denying write access to a particular system file, but it wouldn't dictate how that file could be changed.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] In an RBAC-based system, an operation might be to 'create a credit account' transaction in a financial application or to 'populate a blood sugar level test' record in a medical application.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] A Role is thus a sequence of operations within a larger activity.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] RBAC has been shown to be particularly well suited to separation of duties (SoD) requirements, which ensure that two or more people must be involved in authorizing critical operations.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Necessary and sufficient conditions for safety of SoD in RBAC have been analyzed.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] An underlying principle of SoD is that no individual should be able to effect a breach of security through dual privilege.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] By extension, no person may hold a role that exercises audit, control or review authority over another, concurrently held role.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] A "minimal RBAC Model", *RBACm*, can be compared with an ACL mechanism, *ACLg*, where only groups are permitted as entries in the ACL.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Barkley (1997) showed that *RBACm* and *ACLg* are equivalent.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] For data interchange, and for "high level comparisons", ACL data can be translated to XACML.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control (ABAC) is a model that evolves from RBAC to consider additional attributes in addition to roles and groups.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] ABAC is policy-based in the sense that it uses policies rather than static permissions to define what is allowed or what is not allowed.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Relationship-based access control (ReBAC) is a model that evolves from RBAC.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] In ReBAC, a subject's permission to access a resource is defined by the presence of relationships between those subjects and resources.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] The advantage of this model is that allows for fine-grained permissions; for example, in a social network where users can share posts with other specific users.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] The use of RBAC to manage user privileges (computer permissions) within a single system or application is widely accepted as a best practice.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] A 2010 report prepared for NIST by the Research Triangle Institute analyzed the economic value of RBAC for enterprises and estimated benefits per employee from reduced employee downtime, more efficient provisioning, and more efficient access control policy administration.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] In an organization with a heterogeneous IT infrastructure and requirements that span dozens or hundreds of systems and applications, using RBAC to manage sufficient roles and assign adequate role memberships becomes extremely complex without hierarchical creation of roles and privilege assignments.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Newer systems extend the older NIST RBAC model to address the limitations of RBAC for enterprise-wide deployments.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] The NIST model was adopted as a standard by INCITS as ANSI/INCITS 359-2004.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] A discussion of some of the design choices for the NIST model has also been published.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] NIST Special Publication 800-53, an information security standard used by U.S. federal agencies and other organizations, includes role-based access control in its Access Enforcement controls under AC-3(7).
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Implementations of the CIS Controls, a set of best practices, often incorporate role-based access control as part of fulfilling Control 6, Access Control Management.
[src:aws-iam/role-based-access-control] Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) regulations require implementation of access control as part of technical safeguards for electronic protected health information (45 CFR 164.312), and role-based access control is a typical approach in the industry.
